Do you mind if I touch this PR? I think you're doing it wrong with the imports

> Do you mind if I touch this PR? I think you're doing it wrong with the imports

No problem @YaelDillies. Can you then tell me what's wrong with the imports?

> Glad I checked the list of PRs. I was about to upstream it from PFR 😅 

Sorry. I initially thought it was developed for Carleson, but then I added this PR to the PFR Zulip topic ["Upstream to Mathlib"](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/412902-Polynomial-Freiman-Ruzsa-conjecture/topic/Upstream.20to.20Mathlib) a few hours ago.

Looks great by me now.

maintainer merge
🚀 Pull request has been placed on the maintainer queue by YaelDillies.

Ci failed returning the following warning and error message: 

```console
Warning: ././././Mathlib/Order/BoundedOrder.lean:9:1: warning: unused import (use `lake exe shake --fix` to fix this, or `lake exe shake --update` to ignore)
././././Mathlib/Order/BoundedOrder.lean:
  remove #[Mathlib.Tactic.Finiteness.Attr]
Error: The process '/usr/bin/env' failed with exit code 1
```

I have just run `lake exe shake --update`.

Please add a test file.  You can start with the examples here:
https://github.com/teorth/pfr/blob/ee35aa0228d40a96b36dff66e10b5f420770856e/PFR/Tactic/Finiteness.lean#L65

Build succeeded:
  * [Build](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11569383704/job/32202994352)
  * [Lint style](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/actions/runs/11569383704/job/32202993899)
maintainer merge
maintainer merge
I think the usual rule set pattern would give `finiteness` here rather than `Finiteness`?
I can understand why you want to avoid `intros`, but why `assumption`?
Hmm, not sure. @hrmacbeth, did you have a specific rationale here?
I don't remember, but looking now at the `aesop` docs, it seems that the `-50` is a *penalty*, i.e. (since it is negative) actually an incentive to apply these rules.
Oh! In that case I need to flip my question - why is `intros` given such a high incentive; it seems like introducing the hypothesis `x = ⊤` would be unhelpful?

Very reasonable question :). I see that one of the tests in the PFR version of the tactic addresses this, 
```lean
example {α : Type*} (f : α → ℕ) : ∀ i, (f i : ℝ≥0∞) ≠ ∞ := by finiteness
```
maybe @pitmonticone can report back when he has instituted the test file in this PR.  And also design some other tests which check whether the hypothesis `x = ⊤` is ever being introduced.

It doesn't look like that hypothesis is ever being introduced (according to each of my experiments with `set_option trace.aesop true`), although I don't quite understand why - the tactic sets the intro transparency to reducible, and Ne is a reducible def. 
One thing I notice is that
```
example : ∞ ≠ ∞ := by finiteness
```
fails (as it should) but takes quite a while to get there. Is there a way to hard-code in failure (a cut in the search tree, I guess) for something clearly false? @JLimperg 

Here's what the trace looks like:
```
[aesop] ✅️ (G0) [100.0000%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ ≠ ⊤ ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ R0 [100.0000%] safe|tactic|global|Aesop.BuiltinRule.preprocess ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ G1 [100.0000%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ ≠ ⊤ ▶

[aesop] ✅️ (G1) [100.0000%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ ≠ ⊤ ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ R1 [20.0000%] unsafe|apply|global|ne_top_of_lt ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ G2 [16.0000%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ < ?b ▶

[aesop] ✅️ (G2) [16.0000%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ < ?b ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ R2 [18.0000%] safe|apply|global|Ne.lt_top ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ G3 [18.0000%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ ≠ ⊤ ▶

[aesop] ✅️ (G3) [18.0000%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ ≠ ⊤ ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ R3 [3.6000%] unsafe|apply|global|ne_top_of_lt ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ G4 [2.8800%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ < ?h.h.b ▶

[aesop] ✅️ (G4) [2.8800%] ⋯ ⊢ ⊤ < ?h.h.b ▶

[aesop] 🆕 ❓️ R4 [3.2400%] safe|apply|global|Ne.lt_top ▶
```
I also don't know why the success probability goes **up**!

> It doesn't look like that hypothesis is ever being introduced (according to each of my experiments with `set_option trace.aesop true`), although I don't quite understand why - the tactic sets the intro transparency to reducible, and Ne is a reducible def.

`Ne` reduces to `Not (. = .)` and `Not` is not reducible, so Aesop's `intros` won't look through it. The `builtin` ruleset contains a rule that explicitly calls `Not.intro`.
Ah! That makes perfect sense. I think that clears up all the confusion here, I'll resolve.

> Is there a way to hard-code in failure (a cut in the search tree, I guess) for something clearly false? @JLimperg

No, but I think this would be a very nice feature to have! New issue at leanprover-community/aesop#170.

> I also don't know why the success probability goes **up**!

This is super weird. I investigated a bit, but haven't found the reason yet.
@pitmonticone Can you consult with @JLimperg about whether there is a way to get this working?
Sure, I'll get back to this tomorrow evening.

```suggestion
attribute [aesop (rule_sets := [finiteness]) safe forward] ne_top_of_lt
```

Admittedly, the error message is extremely unhelpful.
@JLimperg should I commit this now?
I have reverted this change because it makes `example {a : ℝ≥0∞} (ha : a < ∞) : a + 3 < ∞ := by finiteness` fail
I agree reverting this change is good, but the comment is now somewhat misleading - let's amend it to say something along the lines of your comment

I have since learned that there is a better syntax for this, something like (untested)
```suggestion
  liftMetaFinishingTactic Mathlib.Meta.Positivity.positivity
```

You should use `add_aesop_rules` here if possible, e.g.

```
add_aesop_rules safe tactic (rule_sets := [finiteness]) (by positivity)
```

Besides being shorter, this ensures that `aesop?` works.

```suggestion
/-! # Finiteness tactic attribute -/
```
This isn't `safe`, it's possible that one of the factors is top and the other is `0`. Perhaps this can be `unsafe 75%`?
This also isn't `safe`, as it's possible that `a = b =  ∞`. I think this can also be `unsafe 75%`.
Would it be possible to also add `finiteness?` and `finiteness_nonterminal`, like for `aesop_cat`?
Doesn't the `enableSimp := false` disable this?
Right, well spotted

```suggestion
example {_ : MeasurableSpace α} (μ : Measure α) [IsFiniteMeasure μ] (s : Set α) : μ s ≠ ∞ := by
  finiteness
```

It's very frustrating that marking this private means the output of `finiteness?` can't be "Try this"-d into a proof, in most cases it seems like `finiteness?` isn't nearly as helpful as one would want...
I tend to agree with you. I've made them protected in the `Finiteness` namespace

Let's add some tests for this. Currently
```
example {a : ℝ≥0∞} : a + 3 < ∞ := by 
  finiteness_nonterminal
```
fails with error that it didn't close the goal, which seems to directly contradict this. If `finiteness_nonterminal` is meant to succeed and leave a < _ as the goal, then you can change lines 62 to 63 in this file to 
```
    (config := { introsTransparency? := some .reducible, terminal := false, enableSimp := false,
                 warnOnNonterminal := false  })
```
Ah oops I forgot half the config indeed

```suggestion
Standard `aesop` syntax applies. Namely one can write
```

```suggestion
/-- 
Test that `finiteness_nonterminal` makes progress but does not fail on not 
closing the goal. 
-/
example {a : ℝ≥0∞} (ha : a = 0) : a + 3 < ∞ := by finiteness_nonterminal; simp [ha]
```
else I think the point of the test-case isn't entirely clear
Done, thanks.
